gallery.description: The flight and back-up crews for NASA's first manned Apollo Block II spaceflight at a press conference and design review meeting at the North American plant.
(description not yet available)
Apollo Atlantic Recovery
Apollo 7 Astronauts (l-r) Walter M. Schirra, Jr., Walter Cunningham, and Donn F. Eisele,  shake hands with USS Essex cooks.
Apollo 7 Astronauts (front-to-rear) Walter M. Schirra, Jr., Donn F. Eisele,  and Walter Cunningham are greeted by officials upon their arrival by aircraft to Cape Kennedy's skid strip today.

Apollo 7 Commander Walter M. Schirra, Jr., right, flew the last 420 miles of his successful space mission in a twin-engine aircraft today between the USS Essex, prime recovery ship, and Cape Kennedy's skid strip.
Apollo 7 Commander Walter M. Schirra, Jr.,kneels on flight deck of the USS Essex to check landing gear of aircraft which later flew him from the aircraft carrier to Cape Kennedy's skid strip.
Apollo 7 astronauts (l-r) Walter Cunningham, Donn F. Eisele, and Walter M. Schirra, Jr., compare notes at a mission debriefing conducted today at the Kennedy SpaceCenter.

Astronaut John W. Young, back-up Command Module pilot for the first manned Apollo mission moves from the center couch position to the equipment bay in the Command Module simulator in Building 5 at the Manned Spacecraft Center.
The prime crew for Apollo 7 mission scheduled later his year went through spacecraft egress training today at the Kennedy Space Center.
Astronaut Donn Eisele waits to have his space suit adjusted preparatory to entering the Apollo 7 spacecraft for manned simulate altitude runs in the Spaceport's altitude chamber.
Astronaut Walter M. Schirra, Command pilot of the Apollo 7 is assisted by a suit technician for the manned altitude run in the altitude chamber.
Astronaut Donn Eisele leaves the Suiting facility in the Manned Spacecraft OperationsBuilding on his way to the altitude chamber.
Astronaut Walter M. Schirra is inserted into the Apollo 7 spacecraft in the altitude chamber of the Manned Spacecraft Operations Building.
Astronaut Donn Eisele, Command Module Pilot for the first Manned Orbital Apollo Mission, Apollo 7, inside the spacecraft in a simulated altitude test.

The prime crew for Apollo 7, the first manned Apollo flight, (l-r) Astronauts Donn F. Eisele, Command Module Pilot; Walter Cunningham, Lunar Module Pilot; and Walter M. Schirra, Jr., Commander, after completing egress training at Galveston Bay, TX.
The backup crew for Apollo 7 (l-r) Astronauts Eugene A. Cernan, John W. Young, and Thomas P. Stafford, after completing egress training at Calveston Bay, TX.

Apollo 7 Prime Crew Members (l-r) Donn F. Eisele, Walter M. Schirra, Jr., and Walter Cunningham relax after today's successful Space Vehicle Emergency Egress tests conducted at Cape Kennedy's Launch Complex 34.
(description not yet available)
The prime crew for Apollo 7, Walter Cunningham, Donn F. Eisele, and Walter M. Schirra, Jr., after completing egress training at Galverston Bay, TX.
Donald Slayton, Director, Flight Crew Operations (l) at the Manned Spacecraft Center, Houston, briefs Apollo 7 Astronauts from left:  Donn Eisele, Walter Schirra, and Walter Cunningham.

A 224-foot-high Saturn IB space vehicle carrying Apollo 7 Astronauts Walter M. Schirra, Jr., Commander; Donn F. Eisele, command module pilot; and Walter Cunningham, lunar module pilot, lifted off on 10/11/68.
(description not yet available)
Astronauts and mission officials held prelaunch conference.

Apollo 7 astronauts breakfast with NASA officials.  Walter Cunningham, second from left; Donn F. Eisele, second from left across table and Walter M. Schirra, Jr., next to Eisele.  Kenneth Kleinknecht, Manager, Apollo S Spacecraft Office.

Apollo 7 astronauts breakfast with NASA officials prior to their launch into earth orbit atop a Saturn IB space vehicle.  Joining the trio at breakfast was James Webb, left foreground, former NASA Administrator.
Apollo 7 Commander Walter M. Schirra, Jr..
Apollo 7 astronauts enter transfer van.
Apollo 7 Command Module Pilot Donn F. Eisele reads about his upcoming earth orbital mission with flight's commander, Walter M. Schirra, Jr.
Apollo 7 lunar module pilot Walter Cunningham pauses during prelaunch breakfast with his two crew members Walter M. Schirra, Jr., commander and Donn F. Eisele, command module pilot.
Apollo 7 Astronauts Donn F. Eisele, foreground, and Walter Cunningham, rear, undergo spacesuit checks.
Astronaut Walter M. Schirra, Jr., enjoys breakfast before boarding the Apollo 7 spacecraft.
Astronaut Donn F. Eisele adjusts communications carrier.
Spacesuit technician Clyde Teague prepares to place communications carries on head of Apollo 7 Commander Walter M. Schirra, Jr.
Astronaut Walter Cunningham takes a break during suiting up activities - Apollo 7.
Astronaut Walter M. Schirra, Jr. relaxes prior to boarding the Apollo 7 spacecraft.

Astronaut Donn F. Eisele confers with Donald Slayton, director of flight crew operations during suiting up activities prior to boarding the Apollo 7 spacecraft.  On chair at right is astronaut Walter Cunningham.
Apollo 7 astronauts suit up prior to beginning an 11 day mission in earth orbit.
In the launch control center at Complex 34, awaiting the liftoff of Apollo 7.  Center Director, Dr. Debus, is at center.  Launch Director Petrone is in foreground.
Apollo 7 Commander Walter M. Schirra, Jr., pauses in front of honor guard on flight deck of USS Essex, prime recovery ship, following his splashdown.

NASA Recovery Team Leader Dr. Donald E. Stullken leads Apollo 7 Astronauts Walter M. Schirra, Jr., Donn F. Eisele and Walter Cunningham across flight deck of USS Essex, Prime recovery ship, following the trio's recovery in the Atlantic Ocean.

Apollo 7 Astronauts (l-r) Walter M. Schirra, Jr., Donn F. Eisele and Walter Cunningham pause in doorway of recovery helicopter which carried them from their landing point to the deck of the USS Essex, prime recovery ship.
Apollo 7 astronauts (l-r) Walter M. Schirra, Jr., Donn F. Eisele and Walter Cunningham received a "red carpet welcome" aboard the USS Essex, prime recovery ship.
President Lyndon B. Johnson congratulated the Apollo 7 astronauts (l-r) Donn F. Eisele, Walter M. Schirra, Jr., and Walter Cunningham via ship-to-shore telephone following the space pilots' recovery.
Navy personnel hoist the Apollo 7 spacecraft aboard the USS Essex, prime recovery ship.

Apollo 7 Command Walter M. Schirra, Jr., waves to well-wishers aboard the USS Essex following his recovery with Astronauts Donn F. Eisele, center, and Walter Cunningham at the completion of their 11-day earth orbital mission.
Pararescuemen attach flotation collar to Apollo 7 spacecraft after it splashed down on 10/22/68 in the Atlantic Ocean.
Apollo 7 commander Walter M. Schirra, Jr. is hoisted aboard recovery helicopter after he and Astronauts Donn F. Eisele and Walter Cunningham splashed down in the Atlantic Ocean.

After their 4.5-million-mile space journey, Apollo 7 Astronauts (l-r) Walter Cunningham, Walter M. Schirra, Jr. and Donn Eisele greet well-wishers aboard the USS Essex, prime recovery ship, following their splashdown in the Atlantic Ocean.

Two members of the first three-man Apollo crew scheduled to orbit the earth later this year, view unmanned lunar module launching (Apollo 5) at Cape Kennedy's Complex 37.  Walter Schirra (l) and Walter Cunningham.
